# PHASE 2 — IMPLEMENT fix round 1 (VERIFY findings)

<role>
Fix the VERIFY finding below within the existing authorized surface (`bin/cli.js`, `tests/cli.test.js`). Do not touch any other file.
</role>

<finding>
```json
{"id":"payout.duplicate-content-not-compared-fully","rule_id":"spec.idempotency.conflicting_duplicate","severity":"HIGH","file":"bin/cli.js","line":85,"message":"Duplicate equality compares only id, merchant_id, type, and amount_cents, ignoring other JSON content. Two events with the same id and required fields but source values \"card-a\" and \"card-b\" exited 0 and produced a payout instead of exiting 2 with {\"error\":\"conflicting_duplicate\",\"id\":\"same\"}.","confidence":"high"}
```

The goal (`.devlyn/goal.raw.txt`) states: "Events with the same `id` and identical JSON content are idempotent and applied only once. The same `id` with different JSON content is a conflicting duplicate." The current `hasSameEventContent` helper in `bin/cli.js` only compares the four schema-defined fields (`id`, `merchant_id`, `type`, `amount_cents`), so two events sharing an `id` but differing in any other JSON property are incorrectly treated as an identical (idempotent) duplicate instead of a `conflicting_duplicate`.
</finding>

<fix>
Change the duplicate-equality check to compare the full JSON content of the two events (deep/structural equality across all properties present on the event object), not just the four defined schema fields. The simplest correct fix: compare via a stable deep-equality check (e.g. comparing `JSON.stringify` of each object with its keys sorted, or an explicit recursive/key-set comparison) so any differing property — defined or not — triggers `conflicting_duplicate`.

Keep the four required-field validation (`validateEvent`) unchanged — that governs which fields must be present/valid, separately from the idempotency-equality check.

Add a regression test to `tests/cli.test.js` asserting that two events with the same `id`, identical required fields, but a different value in an extra property are correctly rejected as `conflicting_duplicate` (exit 2, stderr exactly `{"error":"conflicting_duplicate","id":"<id>"}`, empty stdout).
</fix>

<quality_bar>
- Minimal, targeted fix. Do not refactor unrelated code.
- Do not weaken or remove any existing test.
- Only touch `bin/cli.js` and `tests/cli.test.js`.
- Run `node --test tests/` and confirm all tests (existing + new) pass before finishing.
</quality_bar>

Report your verdict in your final reply text: `PASS` on success; `BLOCKED` if you cannot fix this within the authorized surface.
